==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scrip
<hw>Scrip</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>scrippe</ets>,
probably of Scand. origin; cf. Icel. & OSw. <ets>skreppa</ets>, and also
LL. <ets>scrippum</ets>, OF. <ets>esquerpe</ets>, <ets>escrepe</ets>, F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧charpe</ets> scarf. Cf. <er>Scrap</er>, <er>Scarf</er> a
piece of dress.]</ety> <def>A small bag; a wallet; a satchel.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And in requital ope his leathern <qex>scrip</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrip</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Scrip
<hw>Scrip</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <ets>script</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A small writing, certificate, or schedule; a piece of
paper containing a writing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Call them generally, man by man, according to the
<qex>scrip</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bills of exchange can not pay our debts abroad, till
<qex>scrips</qex> of paper can be made current coin.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A preliminary certificate of a subscription to the
capital of a bank, railroad, or other company, or for a share of other
joint property, or a loan, stating the amount of the subscription and
the date of the payment of the installments; <as>as, insurance
<ex>scrip</ex>, consol <ex>scrip</ex>, etc.</as> When all the
installments are paid, the scrip is exchanged for a bond share
certificate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Paper fractional currency.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrippage</ent>⟦br⟧
